Predicting the Forex market has been a key goal of investigators over the preceding couple of decades. There are two methods to forecast the market: fundamental and technical analysis. \textbf{Fundamental analysis} considers many factors, such as the financial system and political state of a country, the popularity of a company, all inner and exterior buying and selling news, etc. \textbf{Technical analysis} concentrates predicting the Forex market based totally on historic data, in particular, the highest price, lowest price, opening price, and closing price of a currency and the volume traded on a particular day. In this work, we concentrate on technical analysis.

Existing techniques are not appropriate for all currency pairs and may provide better effects for only a few randomly selected ones in specific time-frames. Also, most of existing researches are evaluated only considering their prediction error, without considering the entire effect on a broader trading system where the decision to open a position, i.e. to invest, is as important as the decision to close the position. 

In this article, we propose our reusable trading system extensively trained on historical data, measured at 4-hours intervals candlesticks, of 6 currency pairs: 4 major pairs like GBP/USD, EUR/USD, USD/CHF and USD/JPY, and 2 minor pairs like EUR/GBP and GBP/JPY.  The entire dataset spans from 01-01-2010 till 30-04-2021 and we conducted 
thorough experiments on the aforementioned currency pairs on 3 test sets constituted by the entire year 2019, the entire year 2020 and current time interval for year 2021 (from 01-01 till 30-04) for all the 6 currency pairs. For almost all currency pairs during the three long considered time intervals our system has produced stable and high profitable results. We conclude that the best strategy is to invest simultaneously on all of the currency pairs to reduce the loss risk and stay profitable, since, in financial domain, it is not easy to construct a stable mechanism that always generates profit. 

The remainder of the paper is arranged as follows. Section~\ref{sec:2} presents numerous techniques that have been examined in preceding years and can be categorized into several categories: regression strategies, optimization strategies, neural networks, and others. Section~\ref{sec:3} introduces the fundamentals of Forex, trading system such as Meta Trader 5 as well as technical indicators and trading rules. Section~\ref{sec:tradsys} elaborates on our proposed trading system. Section~\ref{sec:5} presents the results of the experiments on historical data, measured at 4-hours intervals candlesticks, of 6 currency pairs on a long time-frame that spans from 01-01-2010 till 30-04-2021. We conclude our article discussing in the last section the results and possible future directions.
